  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0006",
    "kind": "section_text_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_25",
    "source": "header_anchor",
    "member_count": 4,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_25",
        "observed_type": "section_header",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "Shock therapy comes to Argentina",
        "bbox": [
          0.36068702744030867,
          0.18168604715869893,
          0.6011450322289027,
          0.1947674416494405
        ],
        "order": 16
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_26",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "W THEN JAVIER MILEI waS sworn in as Argentina's president on December 1oth he told the assembled crowd: \"There is no alternative to austerity.\" Instead of rosy promises, he warned that tough times lay ahead. Announcing austerity upon taking office is usually political suicide in Argentina. Yet Mr Milei's sombre message was received with cheers. Fans raised chainsaws into the air, in reference to his promise to cut down the size of the state.",
        "bbox": [
          0.3587786264260448,
          0.20203488376976964,
          0.6413887477123058,
          0.3459821429341514
        ],
        "order": 17
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Others",
        "bbox": [
          0.22328244221353838,
          0.20784883754378375,
          0.2576335871757746,
          0.21656976720427826
        ],
        "order": 19
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_31",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Mauro Roca, the managing director of TCW Group, an asset-management company, says investors are pleased with Mr Milei's pragmatic turn. The new president rose to fame promising to dollarise the economy and shut down the central bank. Yet since being elected in mid-November, he has put plans for dollarisation on hold and sidelined loyalists. Instead, he has stuffed his cabinet with technocrats from the main centre-right coalition, Together for Change, which held the presidency from 2015 to 2019.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6583969430919028,
          0.22585167305478004,
          0.9410322148907768,
          0.39980158747338324
        ],
        "order": 21
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0007",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_17",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Source: Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas",
        "bbox": [
          0.07061068593955264,
          0.2760416667228392,
          0.22900762939123637,
          0.2834821429133154
        ],
        "order": 26
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "> again.\" He wants Canada to be \"an energy superpower\", along with building up AI prowess and building houses \"at a totally different scale\". He is a \"big believer\" in the power of public policy going hand-in-hand with free markets. When asked which political leaders he admires, he includes Mr Harper in a short list, and jokes: \"Clearly he had good judgment in selecting me.\" He is also a fan of Pope Francis and Emmanuel Macron, the president of France.",
        "bbox": [
          0.051526719778042594,
          0.30668604655846604,
          0.34351145010936945,
          0.45213293660694753
        ],
        "order": 27
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0008",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_27",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_27",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The inaugural address set the tone for the shock therapy to follow. On December 12th Luis Caputo, the new economy minister, unveiled a series of radical economic reforms. He announced a devaluation of the peso by over 50%, and promised to slash electricity and transport subsidies, halve the number of government ministries from 18 to nine, suspend public works and reduce federal transfers to Argentina's 23 provinces. The government reckons these cuts amount to almost 3% of GDP.",
        "bbox": [
          0.358778638710343,
          0.34738372092356545,
          0.6412213775823976,
          0.5044642859343103
        ],
        "order": 28
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_32",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_32",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Things may get worse before they get better. In the short term, these measures will lower growth. Given that a cheaper peso, new taxes and fewer subsidies will make living more expensive, there is a chance that prices could rise even higher. Martín Rapetti, a consultant, believes monthly inflation will at least double to around 20% and remain high for several months. But that is far from certain. Mr Milei's emphasis on fiscal discipline may reassure markets that Argentina is not headed for disaster-if they choose to believe him. That would quickly pull inflation down, rather than push it up.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6583969430282894,
          0.40104166645975514,
          0.9408396981930846,
          0.5974702379158849
        ],
        "order": 29
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0010",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_19",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Should he come to power, one of the biggest issues he will have to deal with is economic: the unaffordability of Canadian housing. Since 2000 real house prices in Canada have grown faster than in any other G7 country (see chart). \"People are worried about falling behind as opposed to getting ahead,\" he says. Over the past decade, and under Mr Trudeau's watch, the widely quoted benchmark price of a house in Canada has doubled, to c$760,000 ($560,000).",
        "bbox": [
          0.0609649158145622,
          0.45337301581134265,
          0.3416924962568291,
          0.5974702379522222
        ],
        "order": 30
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0011",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_28",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_28",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Alongside this, however, the administration will increase taxes on imported goods from 7.5% to 17.5%, and extend a tax of 15% on all exports (an existing tax of 30% on soyabean exports will be maintained). Child benefits will double, as will the value of a government food card for the country's poorest. The idea is to cut spending while temporarily increasing taxes to raise revenue, in order to lower the annual deficit from over 5% of GDP today to zero by the",
        "bbox": [
          0.3606870196186201,
          0.5057043650175814,
          0.6412213764135044,
          0.6498015872214452
        ],
        "order": 31
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0012",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_33",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_33",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The confidence of the market \"will depend on the degree of social conflict\", says Mr Rapetti. Since Argentina's return to democracy in 1983, all but one non-Peronist president has been booted out of office by protests against economic reforms. Social organisations were quick to respond to Mr Caputo's announcement. Demonstrations have been called for December 20th.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6582837258651703,
          0.5973837208508911,
          0.9410128236918474,
          0.715116278875579
        ],
        "order": 32
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0013",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_20",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Mr Carney is critical of Mr Trudeau's decision in October to water down Canada's modest carbon tax. He thinks far more could be done to tackle climate change. Just as Canada has successfully exploited its oil sands, he wants it to take the lead developing green technologies such as carbon capture and storage, hydrogen and nuclear reactors. More generally, Mr Carney is among many who acknowledge that, globally, liberalism has taken a battering. The world is at a \"moment...where the accepted forces and policies that have been in place virtually all my adult life are changing\". That is true in Canada, too.",
        "bbox": [
          0.05916031390939621,
          0.5988372095510197,
          0.343511448924573,
          0.7966269841159829
        ],
        "order": 33
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0014",
    "kind": "visual_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_37",
    "source": "visual_seed",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_37",
        "observed_type": "picture",
        "canon_role": "picture",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.3601491943359375,
          0.6653416467718003,
          0.63945029296875,
          0.9514598948029219
        ],
        "order": 34
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0015",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_34",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_34",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Mr Milei may also face pushback from his base and from Congress. On the campaign trail he promised to cut taxes and said spending cuts would be paid for by the \"caste\", a term he uses to refer to corrupt politicians. Yet taxes will now increase sig nificantly, at least temporarily, and austerity will affect far more than just public workers. His coalition has only 10% of seats in the Senate, and 15% in the lower house. On average since 1983, presidents have commanded the support of 45% of Congress, according to Ana Iparraguirre, a political consultant.",
        "bbox": [
          0.6582641366823019,
          0.7180059524842975,
          0.9409794181029137,
          0.9026162791975586
        ],
        "order": 35
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0016",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_21",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Pierre Poilievre, the leader of the Conservative Party, has blamed Mr Carney for Canada's housing woes (because the bank governor loosened monetary policy in 2008). The pugilistic Mr Poilievre seems keen to go head-to-head with Mr Carney, who he says is \"the incoming leader of the Liberal party\". Would Mr Carney's technocratic, globe-trotting persona appeal to ordinary Canadians? Possibly not. But his response to Mr Poilievre's populist brand of politics is unapologetic: \"This is not a time for novices.\"",
        "bbox": [
          0.0610686987534802,
          0.7978670634485588,
          0.3435114467858399,
          0.966569767259574
        ],
        "order": 36
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0017",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026",
    "primary_id": "docling_magazine_TheEconomist.2023.12.16_page_026_35",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
